T1  - Women Entrepreneurs: Moving Beyond the Glass Ceiling
AU  - Brush, Candida G.
Y1  - 1999/07/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1999.2202143
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1999.2202143
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 586
EP  - 589
VL  - 24
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The book ?Women Entrepreneurs: Moving Beyond the Glass Ceiling,? by Dorothy Moore and Holly Buttner, offers an insightful contribution to our understanding of the experiences, feelings, and perceptions of 129 women business owners who left corporations to start or acquire their own businesses. Data collected from 13 focus groups across the United States yield rich stories illustrating the personal transitions of women who left corporate jobs to become entrepreneurs. These qualitative data are supplemented with surveys, the results of which statistically support the themes derived from the focus groups. In their ensuing discussion, the authors compare ?corporate climbers? and ?intentionalists??the former organizational women who were pushed to entrepreneurship and the latter women who planned to be entrepreneurs.
AB  - The book ?Women Entrepreneurs: Moving Beyond the Glass Ceiling,? by Dorothy Moore and Holly Buttner, offers an insightful contribution to our understanding of the experiences, feelings, and perceptions of 129 women business owners who left corporations to start or acquire their own businesses. Data collected from 13 focus groups across the United States yield rich stories illustrating the personal transitions of women who left corporate jobs to become entrepreneurs. These qualitative data are supplemented with surveys, the results of which statistically support the themes derived from the focus groups. In their ensuing discussion, the authors compare ?corporate climbers? and ?intentionalists??the former organizational women who were pushed to entrepreneurship and the latter women who planned to be entrepreneurs.
